properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Periods of rain or freezing drizzle continue to affect Southwestern Quebec. Precipitation is expected to change to showers later this morning or early this afternoon. Freezing precipitation is expected through the end of the day in several areas of Central Quebec. The Saguenay, Montmagny, Charlevoix and Kamouraska areas will be affected mainly in the afternoon. A total of 2 to 4 millimetres is expected depending on the area. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Major winter storm Sunday afternoon into Monday. An intense low from the southwestern United States will bring a winter storm to eastern Ontario and portions of central Ontario late Sunday into Monday. Freezing rain will develop Sunday afternoon in central Ontario and Sunday evening in eastern Ontario then change to rain Monday morning. However, the Ottawa Valley will likely see occasional snow or ice pellets develop Sunday evening then change to freezing rain early Monday morning. The freezing rain may persist into Monday night in some places. Significant ice accumulation will be possible and widespread power outages are expected where freezing rain is the primary type of precipitation. Travel is expected to deteriorate Sunday afternoon over central Ontario and in the evening over eastern Ontario. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds and a mix of rain and snow tonight and Saturday. A sharp trough over the Pacific Ocean will approach Haida Gwaii tonight then reach the mainland coast early Saturday. Strong southeasterly winds will rise as the system approaches, reaching up to 90 km/h on Haida Gwaii and on exposed coastal sections of the mainland. Wind warnings have been issued for Haida Gwaii and the North Coast - coastal sections. Moderate rain will be widespread, but mixed precipitation will occur over inland areas of the North Coast where warm, moist Pacific air will collide with the cooler air in place. Up to 10 cm of snow will fall at Terrace and up to 15 cm at Stewart before the change to rain tonight. There is a risk of freezing rain during the transition from snow to rain. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. Extreme wind chill conditions near -55 will continue tonight and Saturday. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. On Saturday morning, a low pressure centre moving across the northern Gulf of Alaska will result in falling pressure over the Yukon. This will combine with higher pressure over the Northwest Territories will generate strong easterly winds early Saturday morning. The resulting blizzard conditions will affect almost the entire Dempster, including the Olgilvie Mountains. In addition, extreme windchill values near minus 50 are possible. The blizzard conditions are expected to ease through Saturday evening. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
